			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think the driving reason that pets are in their current state is that nothing is mutually exclusive. Any AA will be available to any magician, Any Pet Focus will be available to any magician. Also, if we are given say, increases in defense - we will immediately pounce on the fact that we actually need offense. Vice versa. 
<br />

<br />
Pets are situational, but they cannot be overly powerful in any single area, or else you could combine them to have something too extensive. All pets have relativly similar stats. For damage, Unfocused CoEarth hits 100, Air hits 104 and Water hits 102. For hitpoints Earth is 7K, Air is 5.6K, Water 5K. These are a little more drastic then the hits, but in the big scheme of things not too different. 
<br />

<br />
We will never have a true "tank" pet, because then we could group and have 6 "true" tanks and 6 "true" damage dealers. We will never have a true "dps" pet because then we'd have a dozen damage dealers. They will always fall short of what we'd like them to do. 
<br />

<br />
My solution to this is to make something mutually exclusive. Your pet can either specialize in defense, or offense. This cannot be done with a focus effect. This can not be done with pet revision. Instead I would suggest it through something like pet buffs through clicks. You would do extremely involved (but not raid required) quests and tasks to get each item. The items would serve no purpose except to click the buff onto the pet. You can obtain either Item A, or Item B, but not both, each increasing the pets charateristics in one way specifically. These could be further made into tiers. One for a 50's mage, a 60's mage, a 65 mage, a 70 mage and a Raiding mage. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">For Example of the Offensive:</span>
<br />
Tier 1(50's) 40 ATK, Increased chance to dual wield 5%
<br />
Tier 2(60's) 80 ATK, Increased chance to dual wield 10%
<br />
Tier 3(65's) 120 ATK, Increased chance to dual wield 15%, Over Haste 5%
<br />
Tier 4(70's) 160 ATK, Increased chance to dual wield 20%, Over Haste 10%
<br />
Tier 5(Anguish/Tacvi) 200 ATK, Increased chance to dual wield 25%,  Over Haste 15%, Increase accuracy by 8%
<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">
<br />
For Example of the Defensive:</span>
<br />
Tier 1(50's) 20 AC, Increased Chance to Dodge 8%
<br />
Tier 2(60's) 40 AC, Increased Chance to Dodge 16%
<br />
Tier 3(65's) 60 AC, Increased Chance to Dodge 24%, 300 hitpoints
<br />
Tier 4(70's) 800 AC, Increased Chance to Dodge 32%, 500 hitpoints
<br />
Tier 5(Anguish/Tacvi) 100 AC, Increased Chance to Dodge 40%, 800 hitpoints, 10% chance to resist spells completely
<br />

<br />
This would allow us to have pet increases, that would be singular to us. It would add a potentially fun and extremely rewarding quest, and it wouldn't be over powering because not every magician would choose the same. Soloing magicians may want the defensive, while raiders might want offensive. Not everyone could get it, so there wouldn't be a major concern about stacking with other mages. You could, through great effort, switch from Offensive to Defensive by redoing faction and recompleteing the quest through the other side. 
<br />

<br />
Anyone can get AA's and increase their pets. They are expensive and weak because they are available to everyone. Focus's are not widely available, and the ones that are easy to get (DPOC) offer minimal improvements on the 66+ Pets.  This is partially inspired by epic 1.5 - but it gives both defense and offense. This, once again, makes all pets potentially the same, and therefore all pets must have the same constrictions. 
<br />

<br />
Don't take the numbers to heart on the different abilities. I've no idea how drastically they'd affect pets. Anyones opinions on this?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
