			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Sorry <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile" border="0" /> I have a bad habbit of writting alot to make people think I mean something important <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" /> Blame the school system.
<br />

<br />
My main point was that its not a good idea to give people both defense and offense, and I think the same rule applies to pets. For the mage class itself, this may be a bit lacking (Gate or Pet = uber defense). Look at say, druids. They can load up all their dots, roots, snares and nukes - or their Heals, Buffs and evacs. They become mainly Defensive or Offensive (with the exception that they can have both high offense and defense spells at the same time). 
<br />

<br />
I think their should be more focuses available as well, but I really do think that improvements should be mutually exclusive. This could Apply to AA's - you could either get Elemental Agility and Elemental Durability (for actually good upgrades) OR you could get Fury and Alacrity for actually good upgrades. Not both. The reason they all suck now is because you can have both. Same for Focus's - they are nice, but they don't give appropriate upgrades - the reason is because it improves both offense and defense. 
<br />

<br />
Warriors give up DPS for defense. We give up defense for DPS. Our pets should do the same - make either an item that specializes each pet, or make the focuses do it. 
<br />

<br />
I think thats good enough in size - so I'll leave it there <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
